{"title_page": "Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation", "text_new": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21 November 2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30 August 2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29 February 2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10 November 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=3 December 2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=Master replicators resurrect an ancient Egyptian tomb in Switzerland|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15 November 2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28 October 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22 October 2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17 April 2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=4 May 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=8 November 2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=1 October 2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9|first=|date=2 June 2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23 July 2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "text_old": "The Factum Foundation for Digital Technology in Conservation is a [[Nonprofit organization|not-for-profit organization]]\u00a0founded by Adam Lowe in 2009 and located in Madrid, Spain. It develops new techniques in digital recording and processing to document artworks and cultural heritage of many different types.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/11/28/the-factory-of-fakes|title=The Factory of Fakes: How a workshop uses digital technology to craft perfect copies of imperilled art|last=Zalewski|first=Daniel|date=21 November 2016|website=The New Yorker|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f4f14250-ca3f-11e9-af46-b09e8bfe60c0|title=How digital scanning can help save art works and buildings|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|date=30 August 2019|website=Financial Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elmundo.es/madrid/2020/02/29/5e57cfacfdddfff83a8b471f.html|title=Los copiadores legales del arte antiguo|last=G\u00f3mez|first=Virginia|date=29 February 2020|website=El Mundo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hoy.es/sociedad/taller-prodigios-20191109002812-ntvo.html|title=El taller de los prodigios|last=Guerrero|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=10 November 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/apollo-awards-digital-innovation-year/|title=Digital Innovation of the Year: The Apollo Awards 2014|last=|first=|date=03 December 2014|website=Apollo Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It is known for its facsimiles (high-resolution physical copies) of sites and objects such as the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|title=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/details-pharaoh-seti-tomb-replica-egypt/index.html|last=Glass|first=Nick|date=15 November 2017|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> two monumental [[lamassu]] sculptures from [[Nimrud]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/mosul-statues-unveiling-scli-intl/index.html|title=Mosul takes delivery of recreated icons|last=Guy|first=Jack|date=28 October 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/art-smashed-by-jihadists-rises-up-after-global-effort-g0dbphfd5|title=Art smashed by jihadists rises up after global effort|last=Keeley|first=Guy|date=22 October 2019|website=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jordantimes.com/news/region/replicas-assyrian-statues-smashed-daesh-unveiled-iraqs-mosul|title=Replicas of Assyrian statues smashed by Daesh unveiled in Iraq\u2019s Mosul|last=AFP|first=|date=24 October 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Sebastiano del Piombo|Borgherini Chapel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/372727/how-michelangelo-and-sebastianos-roman-chapel-was-recreated-in-london/|title=How Michelangelo and Sebastiano\u2019s Roman Chapel Was Recreated in London|last=McEwan|first=Olivia|date=17 April 2017|website=Hyperallergic|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The\u00a0 Foundation also mounts exhibitions and trains local communities across the world in the use of digital recording technologies, and is active in contemporary debates about the functions and value of facsimiles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/49/exhibitions|title=Exhibitions|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind/171/trainings-collaborations|title=Trainings and Collaborations|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/the-apollo-podcast-adam-lowe/|title=The Apollo podcast: Adam Lowe|last=|first=|date=4 May 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> It states that its aim is to \u201cbreak down the barriers between traditional and digital arts and demonstrate the importance of documenting, monitoring, studying, recreating and disseminating the world\u2019s cultural heritage.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/aboutus|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFactum Foundation works closely with [[Factum Arte]], and was established in order to take over Factum Arte\u2019s non-profit work relating to cultural heritage.\u00a0 \n\n== Cultural heritage projects ==\nNotable facsimiles made by Factum Foundation include: \n\n* The [[KV62|tomb of Tutankhamun]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-24478909|title=Which would you rather visit - a fake tomb or a real one?|last=Gee|first=Alison|date=08 November 2013|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Rooms from the [[KV17|Tomb of Seti I]] in the [[Valley of the Kings]]. Scanning of all extant fragments from the tomb is underway, and Factum states that the finished facsimile of the tomb will be \u2018by some measures... even more complete than the original as it now stands\u2019, as it will incorporate fragments removed from the tomb in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1502/the-tomb-of-seti-recording-and-facsimile|title=Factum Foundation website|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> \u00a0\n* Two monumental lamassu and all extant wall and floor reliefs from the throne room of the North-West Palace of [[Ashurnasirpal II]] at Nimrud \n\n* The [[:it:Polittico_Griffoni|Polittico Griffoni]], a 15th-century Bolognese altarpiece which was dismantled in the 18th century, and whose 16 separate painted panels are now in museums across the world \n* [[Raphael]]\u2019s ''Sacrifice at Lystra'', one of the [[Raphael Cartoons]] now in the [[Victoria and Albert Museum|V&A Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vam.ac.uk/blog/projects/exciting-new-plans-for-the-raphael-cartoons-and-raphael-court|title=Exciting new plans for the Raphael Cartoons and Raphael Court|last=Steel|first=Sophie|date=01 October 2019|website=V&A blog|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1578/the-tomb-of-raphael-in-the-pantheon Tomb of Raphael] from the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]] \n* Several artworks from [[Horace Walpole]]\u2019s collections for [[Strawberry Hill House]]\n* Two sketchbooks by [[Antonio Canova]]\n\n* The [http://www.factum-arte.com/pag/1331/MINIATURE-BOOK-SCANNER Offiziolo di Carlo VIII] \n* The Borgherini Chapel \n\n\nOther projects have sought to \u2018digitally restore\u2019 artworks to a former state, to recreate lost artworks, or to show artworks in a changed form. Projects include: \u00a0\n\n* Digital restoration of a [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1351/canovas-equestrian-statue monumental plaster horse] by Canova, whose original is now in fragments \n\n* Digital restoration and restored facsimile of the vandalised sacred cave of [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag/1289/the-sacred-cave-of-kamukuwak%C3%83 Kamukuwak\u00e1] \u00a0\n* Recreation of Raphael\u2019s painting [[Christ Falling on the Way to Calvary|Lo Spasimo]] as a painting on board. The painting had been [[Transfer of panel paintings|transferred from wooden boards to canvas]] by restorers in the early 19th century, so the recreation attempts to recover an earlier stage in the history of the work. \u00a0\n* The re-creation of [[Muhammad al-Idrisi|al-Idrisi]]'s lost silver world map \n\n== Technologies ==\n\n=== Technologies for recording\u00a0 ===\nThe Factum Foundation develops many of its own recording and processing technologies, which include the Lucida 3D Scanner (designed by [[Manuel Franquelo]] with the support of Factum Foundation and Factum Arte),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6-8 February 2019|title=A REVIEW OF RECORDING TECHNOLOGIES FOR DIGITAL FABRICATIONIN HERITAGE CONSERVATION|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/2fbe/810138da092f9ba3fcd09b430690c5e310f0.pdf|journal=The International Archives of the Photogrammetry, Remote Sensing and Spatial Information Sciences, Volume XLII-2/W9, 2019 8th Intl. Workshop 3D-ARCH \u201c3D Virtual Reconstruction and Visualization of Complex Architectures\u201d|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Del Sette, Patan\u00e9 et al.|first=|date=02 June 2017|title=Automated displacement measurements on historical canvases|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40494-017-0135-4|journal=Heritage Science|volume=5|pages=|via=Springer}}</ref> the Veronica Scanner,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2016/jul/23/gallery-offers-visitors-a-3d-digital-sculpture-in-four-seconds|title=Gallery offers visitors a 3D digital sculpture in four seconds|last=Alberge|first=Dalya|date=23 July 2016|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> and several book and manuscript scanners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/36/recording|title=Technology: Recording|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> The Foundation also uses established and in-development recording techniques such as [[photogrammetry]], [http://www.factumfoundation.org/pag_fa/1343/panoramic-composite-photography panoramic composite photography], [[Lidar|LiDAR]] and [[White light scanner|structured light scanning]]. \n\n=== Technologies for making facsimiles\u00a0 ===\nTo make its facsimiles Factum Foundation employs a range of traditional and new technologies, often in combination. Technologies include [[Numerical control|CNC-milling]], several types of [[3D printing]], [[Molding (process)|molding]] and [[Plaster cast|plaster casting]], [[Lost-wax casting|bronze casting]], inkjet printing using an in-house printer, sculptural finishing, [[gilding]], [[scagliola]], [[Printmaking|print-making]], and the use of traditional [[Conservation and restoration of cultural heritage|restoration/conservation]] techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.factumfoundation.org/ind_fa/40/outputs|title=Technology: Outputs|last=|first=|date=|website=Factum Foundation website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== External Links ==\n\n* [http://www.factumfoundation.org/ Official website]\n", "name_user": "Anachorism", "label": "safe", "comment": "formatting changes to footnotes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factum_Foundation_for_Digital_Technology_in_Conservation"}
{"title_page": "Delta Fire", "text_new": "{{Infobox wildfire\n|title=Delta Fire\n|location=[[Shasta\u2013Trinity National Forest|Shasta National Forest]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| image               = File:Delta Fire 090518CaltransDist2.jpg\n| caption             = The Delta Fire as it closed of Interstate 5\n|coordinates={{coord|40.891|N|122.228|W|region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}\n|pushpin_map=California\n|pushpin_map_caption=The fire's location in Northern California\n|reference=<ref name=\"Delta Fire\" />\n|cost=Unknown\n|date={{Start date|2018|9|5}} \u2013 {{End date|2018|10|7}}\n|area={{convert|63,311|acre|km2|0}}\n|buildings=20 structures\n|cause= Unknown\n|landuse=\n|injuries=2\n|fatalities=None reported\n|perps=\n|motive=\n}}\nThe '''Delta Fire''' was a wildfire that burned near [[Lakehead, California|Lakehead]], [[California]], in the [[Shasta\u2013Trinity National Forest|Shasta National Forest]]. The fire burned {{convert|63,311|acre|km2|0}}<ref name=\"Delta Fire\">{{Cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/6191/|title=Delta Fire Information - InciWeb the Incident Information System|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|language=en|date=October 7, 2018|access-date=October 7, 2018}}</ref> and destroyed 20 structures, before it was 100% contained on October 7, 2018. The fire burned into the western flank of the nearby [[Hirz Fire]] on September 10, and also burned only a couple of miles away from the enormous [[Carr Fire]], the sixth-most destructive fire in Californian history.\n\n==Timeline==\nThe Delta Fire ignited on September 5, 2018, at approximately 12:51 PM PDT, 2 miles north of [[Lakehead, California|Lakehead]], [[California]]. The fire rapidly grew in size, crossing over [[Interstate 5]] between [[Lakehead, California]], and [[Castella, California]], which forced the interstate to be shut down from September 5 to September 10. On September 10, the fire merged with the nearby [[Hirz Fire]] to the east, and by September 11, the fire was only a few miles away from burning into the already-contained [[Carr Fire]] to the southwest.<ref name=\"KRCR Updates\">{{Cite web|url=https://krcrtv.com/news/shasta-county/delta-fire-tuesday-september-11-remains-5-percent-contained-53311-acres-burned|title= Delta Fire|last=Pike|first=Haleigh|website=krcrtv.com|language=en|date=September 11, 2018|access-date=September 11, 2018}}</ref> On September 12, the Delta Fire reached {{convert|57,253|acre|km2|0}} and was only 17% contained. On September 13, the northern flank of the fire flared up again and shut down [[Interstate 5]] again for six hours during the afternoon. During the next few days, the Delta Fire continued to grow in size, albeit at a slow rate, while firefighters continued making progress on containing the wildfire, with the fire reaching {{convert|60,277|acres|km2}} and 76% containment by September 17.<ref name=\"September 17 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/47999/|title=Delta Fire Daily Update 9-17-18|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=September 17, 2018|accessdate=September 18, 2018}}</ref> On September 18, firefighters had contained most of the Delta Fire's northern flank, while flames on the fire's southwestern flank continued to spread, nearly reaching the Carr Fire's burn area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/map/6191/1/88882|title=Delta Fire PIO Map 9-18-18|author=|publisher=InciWeb|date=September 18, 2018|accessdate=September 19, 2018}}</ref> Late on September 19, the Delta Fire had grown to {{convert|60,592|acres|km2}}, while containment increased to 88%, with the southwestern flank of the wildfire being the only active portion of the fire.<ref name=\"Delta Fire\" /> On September 24, the Delta Fire had grown to {{convert|60,751|acres|km2}}, while containment increased to 98%.<ref name=\"Delta Fire\" /> On September 25, a spot fire broke out in Bear Gulch, outside of the southwestern perimeter of the Delta Fire, which quickly reached {{convert|1,000|acres|km2}} by the next morning.<ref name=\"September 26 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/48308/|title=Delta Fire Daily Update for Wednesday, September 26th|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=September 26, 2018|accessdate=September 29, 2018}}</ref> On September 27, a second, smaller spot fire had broken out to the south of the larger spot fire, situated south of Damnation Creek, which was estimated at {{convert|14|acres|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://krcrtv.com/news/shasta-county/delta-fire-update-thursday-september-27-acreage-grows-from-aerial-mapping|title=Delta Fire Update Thursday, September 27: Aerial mapping shows more accurate acreage|author=Christian Wohlfeil|publisher=KCRC|date=September 27, 2018|accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> The first spot fire continued to spread uncontained, while the main body of the Delta Fire was contained; by September 29, the first spot fire had exceeded {{convert|2,376|acres|km2}} in size, increasing the total burn area of the Delta Fire to {{convert|63,093|acres|km2}}, and dropping the overall containment of the Delta Fire to 97%. The spot fires were at 0% containment.<ref name=\"September 29 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/48464/|title=Delta Fire Update for September 29th, 2018|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=September 29, 2018|accessdate=September 30, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Delta Fire\" /> On September 30, the Delta Fire expanded to {{convert|63,293|acres|km2}}, with containment remaining at 97%.<ref name=\"September 30 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/48491/|title=Delta Fire Daily Update for Sunday, September 30th|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=September 30, 2018|accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> The fire did not experience any further growths for the next several days, while containment generally remained at 97% up until October 5.<ref name=\"October 5 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/48600/|title=Delta Fire Update for Friday, October 5, 2018|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=October 5, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref> Afterward, the Delta Fire experienced another small growth, increasing to {{convert|63,311|acres|km2}}. On October 7, the Delta Fire was fully contained, without any further increases in size.<ref name=\"October 7 update\">{{cite web|url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/article/6191/48631/|title=Delta Fire Update for October 7, 2018|author=|website=inciweb.nwcg.gov|date=October 7, 2018|accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe fire was determined to be man-made, although the exact cause remains unclear.<ref>https://www.abc10.com/article/news/local/delta-fire-latest-maps-and-road-closures/591289213</ref>\n\n==Fire growth and containment progress==\n[[File:After a wildfire is out, our Burned Area Emergency Response teams assess dama....webm|thumb|right|Video from the [[US Forest Service]] about the Delta / Herz fires]]\n[[File:Hot shot spraying water on the Delta Fire (42894188060).jpg|thumb|Fire suppression efforts on September 14]]\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+Fire containment status<ref>{{cite web |title=Incident information - Delta Fire |publisher=InciWeb |url=https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/6191/}}</ref><br /><span style=\"color:#FFFFFF; background:#808080\">Gray</span>: contained; <span style=\"color:#FFFFFF; background:#FF0000\">Red</span>: active; %: percent contained;\n|-\n!Date\n!Area burned<br />acres (hectares) !!Containment\n|-\n|Sept 5||{{convert|5,000|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|0|width=20|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 6||{{convert|22,000|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|0|width=88|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 7||{{convert|31,325|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|0|width=125|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 8||{{convert|40,580|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|0|width=162|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 9||{{convert|47,110|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|5|width=188|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 10||{{convert|49,874|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|5|width=199|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 11||{{convert|53837|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|11|width=215|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 12||{{convert|57233|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|17|width=229|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 13||{{convert|60018|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|26|width=240|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 14||{{convert|60018|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|28|width=240|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 15||{{convert|60018|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|41|width=240|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 16||{{convert|60018|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|64|width=240|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 17||{{convert|60277|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|76|width=241|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 18||{{convert|60277|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|81|width=241|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 19||{{convert|60592|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|88|width=242|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 20||{{convert|60681|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|88|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 21||{{convert|60705|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|92|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 22||{{convert|60748|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|96|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 23||{{convert|60748|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|98|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 24||{{convert|60751|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|98|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 25||{{convert|60779|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|98|width=243|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 26||{{convert|61715|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|98|width=247|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 28||{{convert|62159|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|97|width=248|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 29||{{convert|63093|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|97|width=250|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|Sept 30\u2013Oct 5||{{convert|63293|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|97|width=253|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" |Oct 6 || style=\"text-align: center;\"|--- || style=\"text-align: center;\"|---\n|-\n|Oct 7||{{convert|63311|acre|ha|abbr=values|0}}||style=\"text-align: left;\"|{{percentile|100|width=253|height=15|text-size=10|progress-done-colour=grey|progress-tbd-colour=red|text-colour=white}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[2018 California wildfires]]\n**[[Carr Fire]]\n**[[Hirz Fire]]\n\n{{commons category|Delta Fire}} \n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://krcrtv.com/news/shasta-county/delta-fire-tuesday-september-11-remains-5-percent-contained-53311-acres-burned Record Searchlight Delta Fire Updates]\n* [http://redding.maps.arcgis.com/apps/webappviewer/index.html?id=94b379a91e0f47cb91712da22f603d39 ArcGIS Delta Fire Activity Map]\n* [https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/6191/ InciWeb Delta Fire Map]\n* [https://calema.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=33c284a58166427bab05a115414930ed Cal OES Delta Fire Live Map]\n\n{{California wildfires}}\n\n[[Category:Wildfires in California]]\n[[Category:2018 California wildfires]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox wildfire\n|title=Delta Fire\n|location=[[Shasta\u2013Trinity National Forest|Shasta National Forest]], [[California]], [[United States]]\n| image               = File:Delta Fire 090518CaltransDist2.jpg\n| caption     